@pganssle - I would appreciate if you could take a look at [abalkin/tz](https://github.com/abalkin/tz) and try to come up with use cases where the code using my `tz.ZoneInfo` would behave differently in Python 3.5 and 3.6.

Note that `_DatetimeWithFold` returned by `fromutc()` is simply

```
    class _DatetimeWithFold(datetime):
        __slots__ = ()

        @property
        def fold(self):
            return 1
```

The only issue I can think of so far is the need to override the a few methods such as `replace` that currently return the subclass, but should return the basic datetime.

Other than that, it looks like with my approach it is fairly easy to write fully backward compatible code: just use `getattr(t, 'fold', 0)` instead of `t.fold` and `tz.enfold(t, x)` instead of `t.replace(fold=x)`.

> two times representing two different timestamps comparing equal sounds like it's going to cause a lot of confusion in the future.

This and several related issues were extensively discussed when PEP 495 was developed.  We struck a careful balance between intuitiveness and backward compatibility.  Time will tell whether  we fully succeeded, but now, almost a year after the PEP was accepted and less than two months before Python 3.6 beta, it is too late to make any changes to the PEP.

